riant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Penrise","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish and Welsh: habitational name from any of the places called Penrose or Penrhos: twelve in Cornwall, one in Devon, several in Wales, and one in Herefordshire near the Welsh border. The Cornwall and Devon placenames derive from Middle Cornish <i>pen ros</i> ‘hill's end’ (<i>pen</i> ‘head, top, end; promontory’, <i>ros</i> ‘promontory, hill spur’). The Herefordshire and Wales placenames have the same meaning, derived from the Welsh elements which correspond to Middle Cornish <i>pen</i> + <i>ros</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel De Penrise was born about 1379 as the daughter of William De Penrise and Unknown. She had at least 1 son with William Berry."},"et":{"about 1379–":"umbes 1379–Surnud","1379–Female":"1379–Surnud","1367–1396":"1367–1396","1390–1433":"1390–1433","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1337":"1337","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1379":"1379","1433":"1433","1367":"1367","1396":"1396","about 1379":"umbes 1379","1390":"1390","Berrynarbor, Devon, England":"Berrynarbor, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1379–":"noin 1379–Kuollut","1379–Female":"1379–Kuollut","1367–1396":"1367–1396","1390–1433":"1390–1433","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1337":"1337","about 1390":"noin 1390","1379":"1379","1433":"1433","1367":"1367","1396":"1396","about 1379":"noin 1379","1390":"1390","Berrynarbor, Devon, England":"Berrynarbor, Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1379–":"environ 1379–Décédée","1379